<p>It was asked if we should do another meet, and a lot of people said yes. I‚Äôve pencilled in Wednesday 18th April for the next meet, from 1pm until 3pm. There‚Äôs already a holding event set up <a href="https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/leeds-cross-government-design-meet-2-tickets-43515337546">on Eventbrite</a>.</p>

<p>If you‚Äôre a public sector organisation in Leeds that has space for up to 35 people, it‚Äôd be great if you could offer to host it. All we need is a room with some chairs and a screen/projector. Otherwise I‚Äôll find somewhere.</p>

<p>We‚Äôll be looking at just three sessions next time, so it‚Äôs not too crammed.</p>

<p>Some things people would like to see:</p>

<ul>
  <li>More things that have been made, show and tells, and work in progress</li>
  <li>Examples of where user research findings have influenced service and content design in a given project</li>
  <li>Accessibility and performance</li>
  <li>Hear from people who are <em>actually delivering</em> services that are transforming the user experience</li>
  <li>Case studies of teams doing proper co-creation with users, not just testing a prototype but making together with users in the room</li>
  <li>Group tasks</li>
</ul>

<p>If you think you can do a session on any of the above, <a href="/contact">drop me a line</a>. We try to offer a safe space where you can lead a session whatever your previous experience, and with that comes support leading up to the meet.</p>

<p>Finally, I want to encourage people in non-design roles to come along. You don‚Äôt have to be a designer to come along. It‚Äôs about gov design, not gov designers. The more we share an understanding of what is ‚Äúdesign‚Äù, the more we share what good design looks like, and the more we share how we can go about that the better our services will be.</p>
